+{"id":"bd-ubjtz","title":"PORT: 15 _nss_compat_* NSS compat plugin entrypoints","description":"Add 15 _nss_compat_* NSS plugin entry points to close the libnss_compat.so.2 surface gap. The compat plugin extends files-based passwd/group/shadow lookups with NIS/+@netgroup syntax; when no compat directives are present it behaves identically to the files plugin. Stubs return NSS_STATUS_NOTFOUND with errnop=ENOENT for getXXX_r / setXXX_r / endXXX (matching the files-plugin convention) and 0 for initgroups_dyn (no extra groups appended). Symbols: end{gr,pw,sp}ent ; set{gr,pw,sp}ent ; getgrent_r / getpwent_r / getspent_r ; getgrnam_r / getgrgid_r ; getpwnam_r / getpwuid_r ; getspnam_r ; initgroups_dyn.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-04-26T20:53:21.446752872Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T20:53:21.446752872Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"bd-ubkl7","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] arc4random_buf silently returns with partially-uninitialized buffer on getrandom short read (nbytes > 256)","description":"Location: crates/frankenlibc-abi/src/unistd_abi.rs:3663-3665

Current code:
    pub unsafe extern "C" fn arc4random_buf(buf: *mut c_void, nbytes: usize) {
        let _ = unsafe { syscall::sys_getrandom(buf as *mut u8, nbytes, 0) };
    }

Defect:
- Linux getrandom(2) 'will never return fewer bytes than requested' for size <= 256 when flags=0, but CAN return a short read for sizes > 256 (man 2 getrandom: 'when reading from /dev/urandom a request of 512 bytes may return fewer if interrupted by a signal').
- arc4random_buf discards the return value and does not loop until nbytes bytes have been written.
- BSD contract: arc4random_buf() never fails; the full buffer must be filled with cryptographically strong random bytes. Our impl leaves the tail uninitialized on a short read, silently handing the caller stack/heap garbage in place of entropy.
- Also: if sys_getrandom returns Err(e), we silently return without filling anything, so buf keeps its prior contents — an app relying on arc4random_buf for a session key or nonce gets deterministic bytes instead of randomness.

Severity: HIGH. Security-relevant: any libc consumer using arc4random_buf for cryptographic material over 256 bytes (session secrets, long keys, nonces for bulk encryption) can receive insufficient entropy. The same pattern affects arc4random at line 3655-3658 where the 4-byte read result is discarded, but on modern kernels a 4-byte read cannot short-read in practice.

Fix plan:
- Loop on partial reads until nbytes bytes are written or the call returns Err with a non-retriable errno.
- Treat EINTR and short reads identically (advance the pointer by bytes-read and keep going).
- Add a regression test that requests a 1_024-byte buffer, asserts the full range is written (no trailing zeros region), and a 0-byte request is a no-op.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-23T23:55:15.764518447Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-23T23:56:18.429439715Z","closed_at":"2026-04-23T23:56:18.427213611Z","close_reason":"Fixed: crates/frankenlibc-abi/src/unistd_abi.rs arc4random_buf now loops on partial reads until nbytes bytes have been written, retrying on EINTR and breaking on persistent errors rather than discarding sys_getrandom's return value. null/zero-size inputs are explicit no-ops. Three regression tests added in crates/frankenlibc-abi/tests/unistd_abi_test.rs: arc4random_buf_fills_entire_buffer_past_256_bytes (1 KiB sentinel test that detects any trailing >=16-byte window of un-overwritten 0xA5), arc4random_buf_zero_size_is_noop, arc4random_buf_null_pointer_is_noop. Run: rch exec -- env CARGO_TARGET_DIR=/tmp/rch_target_libc_review cargo test -p frankenlibc-abi --test unistd_abi_test arc4random -> 3/0 passed in 0.00s. aio_suspend regression tests still pass (4/0). (The 4-byte arc4random path cannot short-read on modern kernels so its call-site is unchanged.)","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
